Health Minister Zweli Mkhize has announced that eight more people have died due to the coronavirus, bringing the national death toll to 131. He says 6 783 cases have been recorded, with 2 549 recoveries. Active cases have risen by 489 bringing the total number up to 4 103. South Africa’s infection rate is just 217 new infections shy of reaching 7000. The increase in deaths is recorded from the Eastern Cape with 4 and both Gauteng and Western Cape recording 2 each.  In a statement, the Health Department says as on April the 30th more than 7,2 million citizens have been screened from the Community Screening Program whilst 72 087 had been referred to testing.  Loading… (function(d){var js, id="pikto-embed-js", ref=d.getElementsByTagName("script")[0];if (d.getElementById(id)) { return;}js=d.createElement("script"); js.id=id; js.async=true;js.src="https://create.piktochart.com/assets/embedding/embed.js";ref.parentNode.insertBefore(js, ref);}(document)); (function(d){var js, id="pikto-embed-js", ref=d.getElementsByTagName("script")[0];if (d.getElementById(id)) { return;}js=d.createElement("script"); js.id=id; js.async=true;js.src="https://create.piktochart.com/assets/embedding/embed.js";ref.parentNode.insertBefore(js, ref);}(document)); The Western Cape has the most confirmed COVID-19 cases with 3 044 and 1 624 coming from Gauteng. There are no unallocated cases in the country and the Northern Cape holds the least cases with only 24 cases. 38 people are in the ICU in the Western Cape which recorded an additional six COVID-19 deaths, bringing to 58 the total number of deaths from the virus in the province.    SABC News reports on the latest COVID-19 numbers:   Loading…  (function(d){var js, id="pikto-embed-js", ref=d.getElementsByTagName("script")[0];if (d.getElementById(id)) { return;}js=d.createElement("script"); js.id=id; js.async=true;js.src="https://create.piktochart.com/assets/embedding/embed.js";ref.parentNode.insertBefore(js, ref);}(document));  